{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588526"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:09:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:09:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15164"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15164"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.37,0.11,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66784"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7855"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5363"},{"type":"tags","id":"5366"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66784"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMost cancers that are diagnosed based on prostate specific antigen (PSA) testing are low risk. Up until about a decade ago these cancers were treated with surgery or radiotherapy. Recent studies have shown that most of these cancers, which are small, confined to the prostate, and not considered to be aggressive according to a common grading system (the Gleason score) can be managed by \u0027watchful waiting or active surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive surveillance is a management strategy for men with low-risk prostate cancer that aims to avoid or delay unnecessary treatment while maintaining the ability to initiate curative treatment if needed. One of the strategies is regular PSA testing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the recommended monitoring frequency for PSA testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Every 3-6 months","Every 12 months","Every 18-24 months","Every 2-3 years","Every 5 years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EActive surveillance protocols for low-risk prostate cancer typically include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 3-6 months\u003C/strong\u003E: PSA testing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E: Digital rectal examination\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 18-24 months\u003C/strong\u003E: Repeat prostate biopsy may be considered\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 2-3 years\u003C/strong\u003E is too infrequent for adequate monitoring\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvery 5 years\u003C/strong\u003E would miss significant disease progression\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, prostate MRI is typically performed every 1-2 years. This protocol allows early detection of disease progression while avoiding overtreatment of indolent disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active surveillance for low-risk prostate cancer requires regular PSA testing every 3-6 months and prostate MRI every 1-2 years","Active surveillance allows monitoring of low-risk prostate cancer while avoiding unnecessary treatment","Digital rectal examination is performed annually during active surveillance"],"references":["Pattenden TA, Samaranayke D, Morton A, Ong WL, Murphy DG, Pritchard E, Evans S, Millar J, Chalasani V, Rashid P, Winter M, Vela I, Pryor D, Mark S, Lawrentschuk N, Thangasamy IA. Modern Active Surveillance in Prostate Cancer: A Narrative Review. Clin Genitourin Cancer. 2023 Feb;21(1):115-123. doi: 10.1016/j.clgc.2022.09.003. Epub 2022 Sep 8. PMID: 36443163.","Kinsella N, Helleman J, Bruinsma S, Carlsson S, Cahill D, Brown C, Van Hemelrijck M. Active surveillance for prostate cancer: a systematic review of contemporary worldwide practices. Transl Androl Urol. 2018 Feb;7(1):83-97. doi: 10.21037/tau.2017.12.24. PMID: 29594023; PMCID: PMC5861285.","Romero-Otero J, Garc\u00eda-G\u00f3mez B, Duarte-Ojeda JM, Rodr\u00edguez-Antol\u00edn A, Vilaseca A, Carlsson SV, Touijer KA. Active surveillance for prostate cancer. Int J Urol. 2016 Mar;23(3):211-8. doi: 10.1111/iju.13016. Epub 2015 Nov 30. PMID: 26621054; PMCID: PMC4966658."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15164"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T09:31:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T09:32:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7855"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66784"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonym